TY  - JOUR
AB  - The economic disturbances initiated by war lead to distinct patterns in business cycles. Until shortages restrict output, war demand leads to expansion in belligerent countries. In neutral countries, the early part of a war is conducive to expansion, the latter part to contraction, in production. Immediately after a war business declines because of the reduction in war expenditure. Revival follows when markets are opened and investment is resumed. The level of business in the first decade after a great war depends upon foreign exchange policy. In the second decade, a general return to the gold standard may put pressure on reserves and lead to world-wide deflation. Although it is probably not the cause of long waves, war may contribute to the termination of the upswing and may add to the difficulties of the downswing of the long waves.
